\date{\today}





\begin{abstract}\label{abstract}


In the present article, an analytical solution based on the Laplace transformation for the Dokshitzer-Gribov-Lipatov-Altarelli-Parisi (DGLAP) evolution equations  has been presented at the next-to-leading order accuracy in perturbative QCD. This technique is also applied to the proton structure function, $F_2^p(x, Q^2)$, which leads to an analytical solution for this function in the Laplace space.
We successfully compare the obtained parton distribution functions and the proton structure function with the results from {\tt GJR08} [Eur. Phys. J C53 (2008) 355-366] and {\tt KKT12} [J. Phys. G40 (2013) 045002] parametrization models. We present the results for the separate parton distributions for all parton species. A detailed comparisons also have been done for the analytical solutions of the proton structure function with the corresponding available E665 and H1 DIS data. Our calculations show a very good agreement with the available theoretical models as well as the DIS experimental data throughout the small and large values of $x$. 


\end{abstract}

\pacs{12.39.-x, 14.65.Bt, 12.38.-t, 12.38.Bx}

\maketitle







\section{Introduction}\label{Introduction}


Dokshitzer-Gribov-Lipatov-Altarelli-Parisi (DGLAP) evolution equations~\cite{Dokshitzer:1977sg,Gribov:1972ri,Lipatov:1974qm,Altarelli:1977zs} are a set of an integro-differential equations which can be used to evolve the parton distribution functions (PDFs) to an arbitrary energy scale, Q$^2$.
The solutions of the DGLAP evolution equations will provide us the gluon, valance and sea quark distributions inside the nucleon.
Consequently these equations widely can be used as fundamental tools to extract the deep inelastic scattering (DIS) structure functions (SF) of proton, neutron and deuteron  which enrich  our current information about the structure of the hadrons. The standard procedure to obtain the $x$ dependence of the gluon and quark distributions is to solve numerically the DGLAP equations and compare the solutions with the data in order to fit the PDFs at some initial factorization scale, typically less than the square of the $c$-quark mass Q$_0^2 \lesssim $ ($m_c^2 \approx  $2 GeV$^2$).
The initial distributions for the gluon and quark are usually determined in a global QCD analysis including a wide variety of DIS data from HERA~\cite{Abramowicz:2015mha,Aaron:2009kv,Aaron:2009bp,Aaron:2009aa} and COMPASS~\cite{Adolph:2015saz}, hadron collisions at Tevatron~\cite{Aaltonen:2008eq,Abazov:2008ae,Abulencia:2007ez,Abbott:2000ew} and fixed-target experiments over a large range of $x$ and Q$^2$ as well as $\nu (\bar{\nu}) {\rm N} \ xF_3$ data from CHORUS and NuTeV~\cite{Onengut:2005kv,Tzanov:2005kr}, and also the data for the longitudinal structure function $F_{\rm L}(x, Q^2)$~\cite{Collaboration:2010ry}.
Finally using the coupled integro-differential DGLAP evolution equations one can find the PDFs at higher energy scale, Q$^2$. For most recent studies on global QCD analysis, see for instance~\cite{Harland-Lang:2014zoa,Khanpour:2012tk,Alekhin:2012ig,::2014uva,Buckley:2014ana,Ball:2014uwa,Martin:2009iq,JimenezDelgado:2008hf}.

Some analytical solutions of the DGLAP evolution equations using the Laplace transform technique, initialized by Block \textit{et al}., have been reported in recent years~\cite{Block:2010du,Block:2011xb,Block:2010fk,Block:2009en,Block:2010ti,Block:2007pg,Block:2008xc,Zarei:2015jvh,AtashbarTehrani:2013qea,Boroun:2015cta,Boroun:2014dka} with considerable phenomenological success.
In this paper, a detailed analysis has been performed, using the repeated Laplace transforms, in order to find an analytical solutions of the DGLAP evolution equations at the next-to-leading order (NLO) approximations. We also analytically calculate the individual gluon, singlet and nonsinglet quark distributions from the starting distributions inside the nucleon. We present our results for the valance quark distributions $x u_v$ and $x d_v$, the anti-quark distributions $x (\overline{d} + \overline{u})$ and  $x\Delta=x(\overline{d}-\overline{u})$, the strange sea distribution $x s = x \overline{s}$ and for the gluon distribution $x g$. Using the Laplace transform technique, we also extract the analytical solutions for the proton structure function $F_2^p(x, Q^2)$ as the sum of a flavour singlet $F_2^{\rm S}(x, Q^2)$, $F_2^{\rm g}(x, Q^2)$  and a flavour nonsinglet $F_2^{\rm NS}(x, Q^2)$ distributions. The obtained results indicate an excellent agreement with the DIS data as well as those obtained by other method such as the fit to $F_2^p$ structure function performed by {\tt KKT12}~\cite{Khanpour:2012tk} and {\tt GJR08}~\cite{Gluck:2007ck}.

The rest of the present paper organized as follows:
In Section~\ref{Sec:Theoretical-formalism}, we shall provide a brief discussion for the theoretical formalism of the proton structure function $F_2^p(x, Q^2)$ at the NLO approximation of QCD. A detailed formalism to establish an analysis method for the solution of DGLAP evolution using the repeated Laplace transforms for singlet sector have been presented in Section.~\ref{Sec:Singlet}.
In Section.~\ref{Sec:Nonsinglet}, we also review the method of the analytical solution of DGLAP evolution equations based on Laplace transformation techniques for non-singlet sector. In Section.~\ref{Sec:Proton-structure-function}, we utilize this method to calculate the proton structure function $F_2^p(x, Q^2)$ by Laplace transformation.
We attempt a detailed comparison of our next-to-leading order results with recent results from the literature in Section.~\ref{Sec:Results}. A completed comparison between the obtained results and available DIS data are also presented in this section.
Finally, we give our summary and conclusions in Section.~\ref{Sec:Summary}. In Appendix~{\bf A}, we render the results for the different splitting functions in the Laplace transformed, $s$ space and Appendix~{\bf B} includes the analytical expression for the coefficient functions of the singlet and gluon distribution in $s$ space.




\section{Theoretical formalism}\label{Sec:Theoretical-formalism}

The present DIS and hadron collider data provide the best determination of quark and gluon distributions in a wide range of $x$~\cite{Abramowicz:2015mha,Aaron:2009bp,Aaron:2009aa}. In this article we will be concerned specifically with the proton structure function at the next-to-leading order accuracy in perturbative QCD.
In the common $\overline{\rm MS}$ renormalization scheme the $F_2(x,Q^2)$ structure function{\color{red}{,}} extracted from the DIS $ep$ process {\color{red}{,}} can be written as the sum of a flavour singlet $F_{2,{\rm S}}(x,Q^2)$, $F_{2,g}(x,Q^2)$ and a flavour nonsinglet distributions $F_{2,{\rm NS}}(x,Q^2)$ in which we will have,

\begin{eqnarray}\label{eq:F2p-SF}
\frac{F_2(x,Q^2)}{x} & = & \frac{1}{x} \left( F_{2,{\rm S}}(x,Q^2)+ F_{2,g}(x,Q^2) + F_{2,{\rm NS}}(x,Q^2) \right)   \nonumber   \\
    & = & <e^2> C_{2,{\rm S}}(x,Q^2) \ \otimes \ q_{\rm S}(x,Q^2)    \nonumber   \\
	& + & <e^2> C_{2,{\rm g}}(x,Q^2) \ \otimes \ g(x,Q^2)    \nonumber   \\
	& + & C_{2,{\rm NS}}(x,Q^2) \ \otimes \ q_{\rm NS}(x,Q^2)  \,,
\end{eqnarray}

here $g$ and $q_i$ represent the gluon and quarks distribution functions respectively.
The $q_{\rm NS}$ stands for  usual flavour nonsinglet combination, $xu_v = x (u - \bar{u})$, $xd_v = x (d - \bar{d})$   and $q_{\rm S}$ stand for the flavor-singlet quark distribution,
